"Lady Perfection"

30
00:02:52,880 --> 00:02:55,269
- Good morning, sir.
- Good morning. Any news?

31
00:02:55,600 --> 00:02:58,831
Nothing much, sir. 3 murders,
107 petty larcenies,

32
00:02:59,160 --> 00:03:02,232
an earthquake in South Cockatoo
and...

33
00:03:02,640 --> 00:03:05,871
... a flying saucer, sir.
Anything new on your street?

34
00:03:06,200 --> 00:03:10,079
- New? On our street?
- Hurry up, hurry up!

35
00:03:10,400 --> 00:03:12,436
- On our street?
- I'm coming, mister Willkins.

36
00:03:12,680 --> 00:03:15,148
I'm waiting. Hurry!

37
00:03:16,320 --> 00:03:18,550
I couldn't sleep all night,
I am so eager to hear...

38
00:03:18,840 --> 00:03:21,957
... the end of the story with
Astute Bill!

39
00:03:22,480 --> 00:03:27,110
In last night's edition the
fearless detective finds out...

40
00:03:27,680 --> 00:03:31,832
... that the stolen diamonds are
in the possession of a woman.

41
00:03:32,160 --> 00:03:34,958
I hope you will find out who she
is, Mr. Willkins. - Thank you.

42
00:03:35,240 --> 00:03:38,118
Eddie! My boy went out without
a raincoat!

43
00:03:39,320 --> 00:03:44,075
Eddie! Don't you ever come near
those awful stray dogs!

44
00:03:45,120 --> 00:03:47,395
- Ed, come home!
- Good morning, miss Lark.

45
00:03:47,680 --> 00:03:50,990
Good morning. Just look
at this monster.

46
00:03:51,280 --> 00:03:54,636
To say nothing of his pedigree.
Half poodle, half terrier.

47
00:03:56,520 --> 00:03:58,636
And he took the worst from
both.

48
00:03:58,920 --> 00:04:02,390
Here's your "Dog Herald" with
the results of the exhibition.

49
00:04:02,720 --> 00:04:03,948
Thank you so much.

50
00:04:04,720 --> 00:04:09,077
How many times did I tell you
to stay away from stray dogs!

51
00:04:09,320 --> 00:04:11,311
Go away, fleabag!

52
00:04:15,040 --> 00:04:17,076
Stay where you are!

53
00:04:17,440 --> 00:04:19,590
- Good morning, admiral Boom.
- Are they here yet?

54
00:04:19,960 --> 00:04:22,349
- Thank god, not yet!
- The flying saucer still there?

55
00:04:22,680 --> 00:04:26,116
The papers write that chances
of aliens coming here are...

56
00:04:26,440 --> 00:04:28,351
I don't care what they write!

57
00:04:28,680 --> 00:04:31,638
If there are chances, that
means there is a threat.

58
00:04:32,160 --> 00:04:35,596
- Put your stupid papers into
the mailbox. - Yes, sir.

59
00:04:38,360 --> 00:04:42,558
Wait! What is the weather
outside?

60
00:04:42,840 --> 00:04:45,070
The cool westward wind
intensifies, admiral.

61
00:04:45,640 --> 00:04:49,519
The devices fail me again!
God damn my spleen!

62
00:04:51,760 --> 00:04:55,036
Morning, mister Robertson.
Writing a new song?

63
00:04:55,440 --> 00:04:57,715
- What's it about this time?
- Listen.

64
00:04:59,080 --> 00:05:02,868
Hey you, villainous nanny Cathy,

65
00:05:03,800 --> 00:05:07,839
You left, and the children
have no nanny.

66
00:05:08,800 --> 00:05:11,837
There's noise and din
all over the place.

67
00:05:12,240 --> 00:05:15,312
All hell broke loose without
a nanny!

68
00:05:15,720 --> 00:05:19,030
And I go on condemning her, only
I didn't write that yet.

69
00:05:19,400 --> 00:05:22,233
My sympathy. It is your ad in
the morning paper:

70
00:05:22,520 --> 00:05:24,988
"Jane and Michael Banks, to say
nothing of their parents..."

71
00:05:25,280 --> 00:05:27,350
- And I should add, their uncle.
- Oh yes, uncle.

72
00:05:27,680 --> 00:05:30,035
"... are in need of a good nanny
or governess...

73
00:05:30,360 --> 00:05:32,635
who would go for a meagre
salary. Urgent." - Yes.

74
00:05:32,920 --> 00:05:35,150
I hope you wouldn't have
to wait long.

75
00:05:44,920 --> 00:05:46,035
Hold this, will you?

76
00:05:46,640 --> 00:05:49,996
Hey you, underground admiral!

77
00:05:51,240 --> 00:05:53,800
Quit the masquerade!

78
00:05:54,120 --> 00:05:55,109
Join in.

79
00:05:55,480 --> 00:05:58,392
Hey you, underground admiral!

80
00:05:59,040 --> 00:06:01,918
Quit your masquerade!

81
00:06:02,560 --> 00:06:05,677
Underground admiral,
quit your masquerade!

82
00:06:11,800 --> 00:06:16,715
"... a good nanny... meagre
salary. Address: 17, Cherry St."

83
00:06:17,200 --> 00:06:21,637
Now all we have to do is wait
until nannies come queuing...

84
00:06:21,920 --> 00:06:24,992
... at our porch, eager to get
the most meagre salary.

85
00:06:26,280 --> 00:06:28,669
If we can't offer a big salary,

86
00:06:28,920 --> 00:06:30,592
... it is better that we say so
in the first place.

87
00:06:31,000 --> 00:06:33,594
So far, if crowds do gather
at your porch,

88
00:06:33,840 --> 00:06:36,434
... it is to marvel at your
dear brother - the idler.

89
00:06:37,640 --> 00:06:40,712
Don't you dare call him that.
He writes songs!

90
00:06:41,600 --> 00:06:44,990
He needs peace and seclusion,
and I personally...

91
00:06:45,680 --> 00:06:47,352
I personally understand him
very well.

92
00:06:47,720 --> 00:06:50,154
Father, what else do they write
about the flying saucer?

93
00:06:51,600 --> 00:06:53,830
Maybe. If I were you I would
mind...

94
00:06:54,120 --> 00:06:56,429
my own saucers and not stick my
nose where it doesn't belong.

95
00:06:58,200 --> 00:06:59,872
Oh, my god!

96
00:07:01,520 --> 00:07:04,876
Another earthquake in
South Cockatoo!

97
00:07:06,280 --> 00:07:09,511
Your children are left
without a nanny!

98
00:07:11,080 --> 00:07:14,152
But I just bought shares
of "Cockatoo-orange Co."

99
00:07:14,800 --> 00:07:16,631
I think I am on the verge of
having a nervous breakdown.

100
00:07:17,920 --> 00:07:20,798
You don't concern yourself with
problems of world economy!

101
00:07:21,600 --> 00:07:24,319
I'm enough concerned with having
to economize on everything.

102
00:07:26,080 --> 00:07:28,594
If you wouldn't...

103
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:32,470
... waste so much time on your
"Cherry Street Women's League",

104
00:07:32,640 --> 00:07:35,029
... I'm sure the issue with the
nanny wouldn't be that acute.

105
00:07:35,800 --> 00:07:40,669
So you think women of Cherry St.
must bear with admiral Boom's...

106
00:07:40,960 --> 00:07:42,791
Admiral Boom is not a fool in
the first place...

107
00:07:43,080 --> 00:07:46,595
A reliable cover from aliens
wouldn't hurt nowadays.

108
00:07:47,240 --> 00:07:49,754
- Yes. - George, what are
you conceiving this time?

109
00:07:50,680 --> 00:07:54,468
Nothing. Only to go to work.

110
00:07:54,880 --> 00:07:57,189
- Make money. Make money,
darling. - Father!

111
00:07:57,520 --> 00:08:00,592
Father! You promised to tell us
where money comes from.

112
00:08:02,360 --> 00:08:05,033
Your mother will better tell you
where it disappears.

113
00:08:05,360 --> 00:08:08,432
Have you finished your milk?
Go to your bedroom and play.

114
00:08:09,840 --> 00:08:12,479
Did you hear what your father
said? March to your room!

115
00:08:13,200 --> 00:08:15,156
- Jane.
- I'm coming.

116
00:08:29,080 --> 00:08:32,152
There was a blue luminescence,
then the object disappeared.

117
00:08:32,520 --> 00:08:36,229
Sir Timothy Green from the
Observer smiled skeptically...

118
00:08:36,520 --> 00:08:39,637
and remarked that people are
disposed to wishful thinking.

119
00:08:40,600 --> 00:08:43,160
I can only say that the Eastern
wind is intensifying,

120
00:08:43,480 --> 00:08:46,199
the night will be cool, and
tomorrow it will start raining.

121
00:08:46,720 --> 00:08:50,395
Naum Nohl from the Times wrote:
"Bad weather is popular today".

122
00:08:50,720 --> 00:08:53,757
But let's not grieve, instead
let us think about our health.

123
00:08:54,160 --> 00:08:56,833
And now - morning exercises!

124
00:09:41,080 --> 00:09:43,548
- Shall we play "Hit-ship"?
- We played it yesterday.

125
00:10:07,200 --> 00:10:08,758
What's new?

126
00:10:09,000 --> 00:10:13,437
Admiral Boom is wiping his
periscope. And cursing.

127
00:10:14,200 --> 00:10:18,113
- It's his favorite "God damn
my spleen!"? - Can't hear.

128
00:10:20,680 --> 00:10:26,232
Mrs. Lark came out into the
garden, Robert is in his tent.

129
00:10:31,360 --> 00:10:33,555
Michael! What was that?

130
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:36,036
- I think it was it.
- What?

131
00:10:37,560 --> 00:10:38,675
The saucer!

132
00:10:39,800 --> 00:10:43,315
Remember, dad said they were
luminescent.

133
00:10:48,160 --> 00:10:49,878
Look!

134
00:11:01,240 --> 00:11:03,708
My name is Mary Poppins.

135
00:11:04,880 --> 00:11:07,189
Yes, yes, of course. Please
do come in.

136
00:11:07,560 --> 00:11:09,915
You'll see, they are very
obedient children.

137
00:11:10,920 --> 00:11:14,390
And you will have no
problems with them.

138
00:11:16,560 --> 00:11:19,996
You do have references from
the Nannies' Union?

139
00:11:20,320 --> 00:11:23,869
My rule: no references.

140
00:11:25,200 --> 00:11:28,875
- But everyone must...
- A very old-fashioned custom.

141
00:11:29,640 --> 00:11:32,200
Totally outdated and useless.

142
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:38,036
Please. The children's
room is upstairs.

143
00:11:52,080 --> 00:11:56,949
Jane, Michael, meet your new
nanny - Mary Poppins.

144
00:11:58,760 --> 00:12:00,876
So it's a deal then?

145
00:12:01,160 --> 00:12:05,836
Almost. If I find it suitable.

146
00:12:06,120 --> 00:12:09,317
- Do you want to take us?
- Michael, mind your manners.

147
00:12:10,480 --> 00:12:12,869
I accept the job,

148
00:12:14,880 --> 00:12:16,552
... Mrs. Banks.

149
00:12:19,040 --> 00:12:22,271
"I accept the job, Mrs. Banks".

150
00:12:22,720 --> 00:12:26,110
One would think she was
doing us a favor.

151
00:12:27,200 --> 00:12:28,792
Why not?

152
00:12:30,360 --> 00:12:33,591
Dammit! The Antarctic Bank
went bankrupt!

153
00:12:35,440 --> 00:12:38,955
My money is lost again.
I knew it! I knew it!

154
00:12:40,760 --> 00:12:42,398
I'm in stress!

155
00:12:43,920 --> 00:12:48,118
When you were a common clerk, we
weren't afraid of anything.

156
00:12:49,040 --> 00:12:50,996
A man is bound to get lucky
some time.

157
00:13:02,600 --> 00:13:06,513
Mr. Banks, would you turn off
that music, if you please.

158
00:13:07,040 --> 00:13:09,600
I personally prefer live music.

159
00:13:09,960 --> 00:13:12,349
- What's live music?
- All in it's time.

160
00:13:13,760 --> 00:13:17,878
It is live music that gives me
real pleasure.

161
00:13:19,440 --> 00:13:20,873
I hope, you feel the same.

162
00:13:22,120 --> 00:13:24,111
And remember once and for all:

163
00:13:24,800 --> 00:13:29,669
... Mary Poppins doesn't repeat
twice.

164
00:13:36,920 --> 00:13:39,354
She must have come here
in a flying saucer.

165
00:13:40,040 --> 00:13:43,112
I knew right away. You are a
humanoid.

166
00:13:44,080 --> 00:13:48,073
You came so suddenly, as if you
were carried by a gust of wind.

167
00:13:48,600 --> 00:13:50,113
It is exactly so.

168
00:13:50,520 --> 00:13:52,033
Do you understand?

169
00:13:54,440 --> 00:13:56,078
I understand!

170
00:13:56,840 --> 00:13:58,956
Speaking of live music.

171
00:13:59,800 --> 00:14:03,839
Piano by "Madam Corry", early
20 century, modern.

172
00:14:04,360 --> 00:14:07,432
But that doesn't mean you don't
have to drink up your milk.

173
00:14:53,360 --> 00:14:55,271
And now...

174
00:14:59,240 --> 00:15:00,434
Go to sleep!

175
00:15:51,120 --> 00:15:55,352
Mary Poppins, you won't ever
leave us, will you?

176
00:15:55,840 --> 00:15:57,273
You won't leave us?

177
00:15:57,560 --> 00:16:01,189
Another word from that corner,
and I will call a policeman.

178
00:16:05,480 --> 00:16:07,948
We just wanted to say, we...

179
00:16:08,280 --> 00:16:11,795
... know you will stay with us
for a long time.

180
00:16:14,280 --> 00:16:15,872
I will.

181
00:16:26,480 --> 00:16:29,074
I will stay, until the wind
changes direction.

182
00:16:30,600 --> 00:16:31,874
It is so good!

183
00:16:32,360 --> 00:16:33,873
It is wonderful!

184
00:17:27,480 --> 00:17:32,156
From year to year the weather
changes.

185
00:17:33,560 --> 00:17:38,759
Bad weather becomes popular
nowadays. Bad weather!

186
00:17:39,960 --> 00:17:44,397
Water gushes in on us from the
sky as though from a water-pipe.

187
00:17:45,400 --> 00:17:49,916
Bad weather stays on for 6
months, and there's nowhere...

188
